  "local_port": 52648,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the differences between RTGS and NEFT?",
  "response": "RTGS (Real-Time Gross Settlement) and NEFT (National Electronic Funds Transfer) are two electronic payment systems used for transferring money between banks in India. Here are the key differences between them:\n\n1. **Settlement Speed**:\n   - **RTGS**: Transactions are settled in real-time, meaning the funds are transferred immediately from one bank to another.\n   - **NEFT**: Transactions are processed in batches, typically settled at specific intervals throughout the day, which can result in some delay before the funds are credited to the beneficiary's account.\n\n2. **Minimum and Maximum Amount**:\n   - **RTGS**: This system is used for high-value transactions, with a minimum limit (usually around INR 2 lakh) but no maximum limit.\n   - **NEFT**: This system can be used for any amount, with no minimum limit, making it suitable for smaller transactions.\n\n3. **Time of Operation**:\n   - **RTGS**: Operates during designated banking hours, generally from 7:00 AM to 6:00 PM on working days.\n   - **NEFT**: Available 24/7, including weekends and holidays, which allows for more flexibility in initiating transfers.\n\n4. **Transaction Fees**:\n   - **RTGS**: Usually involves a higher fee compared to NEFT, due to its real-time service for high-value transactions.\n   - **NEFT**: Generally has lower transaction fees and may even be free for certain amounts as per bank policies.\n\n5. **Purpose**:\n   - **RTGS**: Typically used for high-value, urgent transfers, such as large payments in business transactions.\n   - **NEFT**: More suitable for regular, non-urgent payments like utility bills, smaller personal transfers, etc.\n\n6. **Reversal and Cancellation**:\n   - **RTGS**: Once a transaction is completed, it cannot be reversed or cancelled.\n   - **NEFT**: There is a provision for reversal or cancellation of transactions under certain conditions until the processing is completed.\n\n7. **Availability**:\n   - **RTGS**: Not all banks or branches may support RTGS, especially smaller banks.\n   - **NEFT**: More widely available and supported by virtually all banks in India.\n\nThese differences highlight the suitability of each method depending on the needs of the user, whether they are looking for instant high-value transfers (RTGS) or routine smaller transactions (NEFT).",
